title('Smoothness Sweep in 1D');








The example comments note that extremely tiny values can make the system ill-conditioned, which is exactly why log-step sweeps are better than random tweaking.

Residual-Driven Iteration Idea
For \(A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}\), let
\[
\mathbf{r}^{(k)}=\mathbf{b}-A\mathbf{x}^{(k)}
    ag{1}
\]
be the residual. SOR introduces a relaxation parameter \(\omega\) to accelerate convergence relative to Gauss-Seidel.






TipTheorem - SOR Iteration



With \(A=D-L-U\) and \(0&lt;\omega&lt;2\), SOR is \[
\mathbf{x}^{(k+1)}=(D-\omega L)^{-1}\!\left[(1-\omega)D+\omega U\right]\mathbf{x}^{(k)}
+\omega(D-\omega L)^{-1}\mathbf{b}.
    ag{2}
\] When \(\omega=1\), this reduces to Gauss-Seidel.

